y: analysing the gender dimensions of contemporary processes of marketisation</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F034288/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Tourism is increasingly being pursued as a development strategy for many countries throughout the world.&amp;nbsp; As a growing global industry that draws in ever larger numbers of the world?s population, it is an important focus of contemporary analyses of global political economy.&amp;nbsp; This project focuses on the region of Central America, analysing the ways in which tourism connects outward-oriented growth strategies with poverty reduction projects funded by donor agencies.&amp;nbsp; The research employs a feminist political economy theoretical approach and involves a commitment to linking qualitative research at the local level with analyses of global processes.&amp;nbsp; Drawing on qualitative research in Costa Rica, Honduras and Belize, the project analyses a number of donor-funded projects in order to explore the ways in which tourism reshapes local and national development.&amp;nbsp; In particular, it focuses on a World Bank project in Honduras and an Inter-American Development Bank project in Belize which aim to integrate marginalised indigenous women into the tourist economy.&amp;nbsp; The Fellowship will explore the implications of the findings for our understandings of contemporary capitalist development and its impact on gendered power relations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; 
